{"timestamp": "2025-12-06 10:46:01.011291", "event": "llm_end", "text": "Troubleshooting Diagnosis Report\n\nSummary of network health\n- Layer-3 routing: Healthy. OSPF is running and correctly advertising the expected subnets and inter-area links. All core and distribution routers and the server_access_router have consistent OSPF configurations:\n  - server_access_router advertises 10.200.0.0/24 into area 0.\n  - dist routers advertise 10.1.1.0/24 and 10.2.1.0/24 into area 1, with area 0 links towards core.\n- End-to-end reachability: ICMP between hosts and server farm is good (0% loss, low RTTs). Both hosts can ping the DNS server, load balancer, and web servers.\n- Server-side HTTP availability: Load balancer and all web servers are listening on TCP/80 and have no restrictive firewall rules (INPUT/FORWARD/OUTPUT ACCEPT observed). Server_access_router shows no restrictive filtering.\n- DNS resolution: Fast on both hosts (name lookup time ~3–12 ms observed), indicating DNS is not the limiting factor.\n\nDetected anomalies\n- host_2_1_1_1 cannot establish TCP/80 connections to any target (load balancer, web servers, even direct IPs), while host_1_1_1_1 can.\n- Symptom pattern:\n  - host_2_1_1_1:\n    - curl to http://web99.local, http://10.200.0.7, http://10.200.0.3, http://10.200.0.8 all show total ~5.0s with zero connect/starttransfer reported, indicating connection attempts are dropped/timed out.\n    - Raw TCP connect test to 10.200.0.7:80 hangs until timeout.\n    - ICMP to the same targets is fine; iperf to non-HTTP port (5201) succeeds at ~45 Mbit/s to the load balancer, proving general L3/TCP works.\n  - host_1_1_1_1:\n    - curl to http://web99.local and http://web0.local succeeds (~1.0–1.1s).\n    - Raw TCP connect to 10.200.0.7:80 completes immediately (rc:0).\n- This isolates the issue to host_2_1_1_1 and specifically to TCP port 80 traffic.\n\nLocalization of the fault\n- The fault is local to host_2_1_1_1 (client-side).\n- Evidence from host_2_1_1_1 indicates an active nftables filter drop policy for TCP/80 in all chains:\n  - table inet filter:\n    - chain input: tcp dport 80 drop\n    - chain forward: tcp dport 80 drop\n    - chain output: tcp dport 80 drop\n- No other devices in the path show filtering on TCP/80:\n  - Load balancer and web servers have INPUT/FORWARD/OUTPUT ACCEPT (and listen on 0.0.0.0:80).\n  - server_access_router and core/dist routers have no restrictive firewall entries.\n  - Successful iperf from host_2_1_1_1 to 10.200.0.7:5201 confirms path is fine for non-HTTP TCP traffic.\n\nRoot cause\n- Misconfiguration on host_2_1_1_1’s local firewall (nftables) that drops all TCP traffic to/from port 80:\n  - This directly explains:\n    - 5-second curl timeouts (SYN packets dropped, no SYN-ACK, connection attempt times out).\n    - Raw TCP connect tests hanging.\n    - Normal ICMP and non-HTTP TCP behavior.\n  - DNS works (UDP 53 not blocked), confirming the issue is not name resolution.\n\nSupporting evidence (selected)\n- host_2_1_1_1 firewall rules:\n  - table inet filter:\n    - input { tcp dport 80 drop }\n    - forward { tcp dport 80 drop }\n    - output { tcp dport 80 drop }\n- host_2_1_1_1 curl tests:\n  - http://web99.local and http://10.200.0.7: total ~5.00s, connect/starttransfer 0.000 (consistent with drop/timeout).\n- host_1_1_1_1 curl and TCP connect:\n  - http://web99.local/http://web0.local success; TCP connect to 10.200.0.7:80 returns rc:0 immediately.\n- Pings:\n  - Both hosts to servers and load balancer: 0% loss, low RTTs.\n- netstat on servers:\n  - load_balancer and web_server_0..3: tcp 0 0 0.0.0.0:80 LISTEN; no restrictive firewall.\n- OSPF configs:\n  - server_access_router: network 10.200.0.0/24 area 0\n  - router_dist_2_1: network 10.2.1.0/24 area 1\n  - core_1/core_2/core_3 linking areas 0 and 1 appropriately.\n\nImpact assessment\n- Impacted: HTTP access (TCP/80) from host_2_1_1_1 to all destinations (web99.local/load balancer, all web servers, and any other HTTP service).\n- Not impacted: ICMP, DNS resolution, and other TCP ports (e.g., iperf on 5201), and host_1_1_1_1’s access to all services.\n\nConclusion\n- The network (routing, switching, and servers) is generally healthy.\n- A client-specific firewall misconfiguration on host_2_1_1_1 is blocking TCP/80, preventing that host from accessing HTTP services while all other traffic remains normal.", "generation_info": {"finish_reason": "stop", "logprobs": null}, "invalid_tool_calls": [], "usage_metadata": {"input_tokens": 16755, "output_tokens": 3674, "total_tokens": 20429, "input_token_details": {"audio": 0, "cache_read": 16256}, "output_token_details": {"audio": 0, "reasoning": 2432}}}
